In the 
``` div.post h3 {} ``` 
add 
``` 
   margin: 0;
   position: relative;
   top: 50%;
   transform: translateY(-50%); 
```

This is how you can align any element vertically within another element.

That `List&lt;? extends Number&gt; list` parameter allows to read a list of `Number` or its subclasses.
You want to use `List&lt;? super Number&gt; list` parameter for adding elements in the List but you could add only `Number` or superclass instances of that.    
So your current implementation could not compile either.    

That could work for example :   

    public static void fill(List&lt;? super Integer&gt; list) {
       for (int i=0; i &lt; 10; i++) {
          list.add(i);
       }
    }

And you could pass as parameter a variable declared as List of Integer or List of Number or any superclass.

_is that what You want?_

    public static void fill( List&lt;Number&gt; list ) {
      for( int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++ ) {
        list.add( Integer.valueOf( i ) );
      }
    }

a possible call would be:

    ArrayList&lt;Number&gt; a = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    fill( a );

the list can hold `Long`, `Float` and `Double` as well

